                <h3 align="center">How our crop recommendations work</h3>
                <br/>
                <div class="home_info">
                    <p>The crop recommendations in this app follow the principle of crop rotation. Crop rotation involves growing different crops on arable land to keep the nutrient content in the soil balanced. Most crop families require the same the nutrients from soil, however they all drain nutrients at different quantites. So if one crop family was to be repeatly used on arable land, that family's most required nutrients in the soil will be depeleted quickly, however other nutrients in the soil which the family does not require, will not be put to use. Crop rotation also reduces the build-up of crop-specific pest and crop diseases.</p>
                    <br/>
                    <p><b>Crop families recommendation order:</b></p>
              
                    <p>1. Brassicaceae (Brassicas/Crucifiers)</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Crops - Broccoli, cabbages, and turnips.</li>
                        <li>Most required nutrient(s): Calcium and nitrogen.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <br/>
              
              
                    <p>2. Apiaceae (Umbellifera/Umbels)</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Crops - Carrots and parsnips.</li>
                        <li>Most required nutrient(s): Calcium and potassium.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <br/>
              
              
                    <p>3. Cucurbitaceae (Cucurbits)</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Crops - Cucumbers, pumpkins, squashes and melons.</li>
                        <li>Most required nutrient(s): Phosphorus and potassium.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <br/>
              
              
                    <p>4. Solanaceae (Nightshades)</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Crops - Peppers, potatoes, and tomatoes.</li>
                        <li>Most required nutrient(s): Nitrogen and phosphorus.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <br/>
              
              
                    <p>5. Liliaceae (Allium)</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Crops - Onions.</li>
                        <li>Most required nutrient(s): Nitrogen and potassium.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <br/>
              
              
                    <p>6. Fabaceae (Legumes)*</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Crops - Beans, lentils, and peas.</li>
                        <li>Most required nutrient(s): Balanced and low quantities amoungst general crop nutrients.</li>
                        <li>* These crops have relationships with bacteria that involves the formation of nitrogen that can be absorbed into soil.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <br/>
              
              
                    <p>7. Rosaceae (Rose family)</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Crops - Strawberries.</li>
                        <li>Most required nutrient(s): Calcium, nitrogen and potassium.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <br/>
              
              
                    <p>8. Chenopodiaceae (Chenopods)</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Crops - Beetroots and spinach.</li>
                        <li>Most required nutrient(s): Nitrogen and potassium.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <br/>
              
              
                    <p>9. Poaceae (Gramineae)</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Crops - Corn, rice, sugarcane, and wheat.</li>
                        <li>Most required nutrient(s): Nitrogen and phosphate.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <br/>
              
              
                    <p>10. Asteraceae (Chicories)</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Crops - Lettuce.</li>
                        <li>Most required nutrient(s): Nitrogen and potassium.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <br/>
                </div>
